Aim

Develop methods to identify shared mechanisms between complex diseases and molecular changes in T21.

Hypthesis

Our working hypothesis is that T21-induced gene expression produces unique, variable, and cascading effects in gene regulatory networks - following the recently proposed omnigenic model - that manifest in DS co-occurring conditions through mechanisms parallel, but modified, compared to the D21 population. To identify convergence, we will connect machine learning-derived gene expression modules (MLDMs) extracted from public data with genetic associations for co-occurring conditions in T21 and D21.

Hypthesis - Omnigenic model of complex traits

A central goal of genetics is to understand the links between genetic variation and disease. Intuitively, one might expect disease-causing variants to cluster into key pathways that drive disease etiology. But for complex traits, association signals tend to be spread across most of the genomeâincluding near many genes without an obvious connection to disease.

Hypthesis - Omnigenic model of complex traits

We propose that gene regulatory networks are sufficiently interconnected such that all genes expressed in disease-relevant cells are liable to affect the functions of core disease-related genes and that most heritability can be explained by effects on genes outside core pathways. We refer to this hypothesis as an ââomnigenicââ model.

Hypthesis - Omnigenic model of complex traits

Omnigenic Model: This model posits that the genetic architecture of complex traits involves not only a small number of core genes directly related to a trait but also a vast number of peripheral genes that exert their effects through regulatory networks. This framework suggests that virtually all genes expressed in disease-relevant tissues could contribute to the heritability of complex traits, albeit indirectly.

According to the omnigenic model, the heritability of complex traits is distributed across many genes, including those not directly involved in the disease processes but influencing the trait through complex gene networks. This challenges the traditional focus on identifying âcandidate genesâ and highlights the importance of considering broad regulatory networks.

This hypothesis aligns with the omnigenic model of complex traits, which posits that a few âcoreâ genes in relevant biological pathways and a plethora of âperipheralâ genes, which are indirectly involved through gene regulatory networks, contribute to the genetic architecture of complex diseases and traits.
